You don’t *need* a “real website” yet—Apple just needs **public HTTPS URLs** that load without login. Fastest options:

### Option A (fastest): Notion public pages
- Create 2 Notion pages: **Privacy Policy** and **Support**
- Paste the contents of:
  - `docs/appstore/PRIVACY_POLICY.md`
  - `docs/appstore/SUPPORT.md`
- Click **Share → Publish to web**
- Copy the public links and paste into **App Store Connect → App Information → Privacy Policy URL / Support URL**
- Sanity check: open each link in an **incognito window** (should work)

### Option B: Google Docs
- Create 2 Google Docs, paste the text
- **File → Share → Publish to web** (or “Anyone with the link can view”)
- Use those URLs in App Store Connect
- Incognito check again

### Option C: GitHub Pages (free “website”)
- Create a GitHub repo (or use your existing one) via the **GitHub website**
- Add two files in the repo (via **Add file → Create new file**):
  - `privacy-policy.md` (paste policy)
  - `support.md` (paste support)
- In repo settings: **Settings → Pages → Deploy from branch**
- You’ll get a `https://<user>.github.io/<repo>/...` site; use those URLs

If you tell me which option you want (Notion / Google Docs / GitHub Pages) and whether you already have a domain like `freestylefit.app`, I’ll give you the exact click-by-click path for that choice.

### GitHub Pages (no terminal / no git) — fastest setup

#### 1) Create a repo on GitHub
- Go to GitHub → **New repository**
- Name: `freestylefit-legal` (or similar)
- Choose **Public** (Pages on private repos may require a paid plan)
- Check **Add a README**
- Create repo

#### 2) Add the pages as files (in the GitHub website)
In the repo:
- Click **Add file → Create new file**
- Create `privacy-policy.md`
- Paste the contents of `docs/appstore/PRIVACY_POLICY.md`
- Commit

Repeat:
- Create `support.md`
- Paste the contents of `docs/appstore/SUPPORT.md`
- Commit

#### 3) Turn on GitHub Pages
- Repo **Settings → Pages**
- **Build and deployment**
  - **Source**: “Deploy from a branch”
  - **Branch**: `main`
  - **Folder**: `/ (root)`
- Click **Save**

Wait ~30–120 seconds; refresh that page until you see: **“Your site is published at …”**

#### 4) Copy the final URLs
Your links will be:
- **Privacy Policy URL**: `https://YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME.github.io/freestylefit-legal/privacy-policy`
- **Support URL**: `https://YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME.github.io/freestylefit-legal/support`

#### 5) Sanity check (important)
- Open each link in an **incognito/private window** (must load without signing in)

### How to publish on GitHub Pages using your existing repo

You already have the repo here: [`https://github.com/siestheapp/tryon`](https://github.com/siestheapp/tryon). I added GitHub-Pages-friendly pages under `docs/`:
- `docs/index.md`
- `docs/appstore/index.md`
- `docs/appstore/privacy-policy.md`
- `docs/appstore/support.md`

#### 1) Push the latest changes to GitHub
However you normally do it (commit + push). I won’t run git commands unless you ask.

#### 2) Enable GitHub Pages (serving from `/docs`)
On GitHub (repo page) → **Settings → Pages**
- **Build and deployment**
  - **Source**: Deploy from a branch
  - **Branch**: `main`
  - **Folder**: `/docs`
- Click **Save**

Wait a minute; GitHub will show **“Your site is published at …”**

#### 3) Use these URLs in App Store Connect
Assuming Pages is enabled for `siestheapp/tryon`, your URLs will be:

- **Privacy Policy URL**: `https://siestheapp.github.io/tryon/appstore/privacy-policy`
- **Support URL**: `https://siestheapp.github.io/tryon/appstore/support`

#### 4) Quick sanity check
Open both links in an **incognito window** — they must load with no login.

If you want, tell me when you’ve enabled Pages and I’ll help you verify the URLs/paths match what GitHub generated.

### Typical timing
- **First time enabling Pages**: usually **1–5 minutes**, sometimes up to **10–20 minutes**.
- **Subsequent updates after pushes**: usually **under 1–3 minutes**.

### How to tell it’s live
- Go to **Repo → Settings → Pages** and look for **“Your site is published at …”** plus a green check / “Deployed”.
- Then open the URLs in an **incognito window**:
  - `https://siestheapp.github.io/tryon/appstore/privacy-policy`
  - `https://siestheapp.github.io/tryon/appstore/support`

### If it’s not showing after ~20 minutes
- Make sure Pages is set to **Branch: `main`** and **Folder: `/docs`**
- Confirm `docs/index.md` exists (it does) and that you saved the Pages settings.

<think><details><summary>Thought Process</summary>
**Troubleshooting log errors**

It looks like the snapshot isn't showing log details because of a loading error. There's a message about needing to reload the page, which makes me wonder if I need to sign in, though it might not be necessary. The annotation row provides some info, indicating that the config file is being read. I suspect the Jekyll build is failing, possibly due to a missing theme. Maybe I need to consider adding a custom workflow for GitHub Actions to avoid this build issue.
**Exploring Jekyll build issues**

I’m considering using a `.nojekyll` file and prebuilt HTML to bypass the Jekyll build step. If the `.nojekyll` file is at the root of the published source, it might help GitHub Pages skip Jekyll conversion entirely. But there's still the concern about the `docs/_config.yml` file. Right now, it only has `permalink: pretty`, which seems fine, but the default theme might be causing issues. I'm also worried that content in `docs/error.md` could contain Liquid tags `{{}}` that are causing build errors.
**Investigating error document implications**

I'm considering that the `error.md` file could have lots of placeholders like `{{ message }}` from earlier web searches since it seems to be an output of expo error documents. If it contains these placeholders, it might cause Liquid templating errors if Jekyll processes it, but only if it has front matter. Jekyll processes all markdown files, but only those with YAML front matter are treated as pages. If `docs/error.md` lacks front matter, it'll be copied as-is without causing Liquid errors, so maybe the concern isn't as pressing after all.
**Considering GitHub Pages build options**

I’m reflecting on how GitHub Pages builds using Jekyll, which will still read and copy large files, potentially causing size issues—though that might be fine. I wonder if the failure is related to the path `docs/appstore/privacy-policy.md` that has front matter. Since I can't access logs, I could try reproducing the build locally, but running Node isn't allowed, and I may not have Ruby set up. Perhaps the simplest solution is to disable the Jekyll build by using static HTML, adding a `.nojekyll` file, which would help bypass Jekyll and just publish static assets.
**Preparing HTML for GitHub Pages**

I realize I need actual HTML files because GitHub Pages will serve markdown as plain text, though Apple might accept plain text. Still, it's better to have HTML for readability. I can quickly create HTML pages like `docs/appstore/privacy-policy/index.html` and `docs/index.html`, adding a `.nojekyll` file to avoid Jekyll processing. By deploying from `/docs`, I'll ensure pretty URLs. I’ll also make sure the content matches the policy and support, and then I'll commit and push everything, including new directories for the HTML files.</details></think>

### Cheapest options for `freestylefit.net` email

#### Option A (cheapest/free): **Forwarding only** (receive email, not ideal for sending)
- Use **GoDaddy Email Forwarding** (often included with the domain).
- Create forwards like `support@freestylefit.net` → your Gmail.
- Good enough for App Store requirements if you just need a contact inbox.

**Downside:** replying “from” `support@freestylefit.net` is clunky unless you also pay for a sending mailbox somewhere.

#### Option B (best cheap “real email”): **iCloud+ custom domain** (send/receive)
- If you already pay for iCloud+ (starts at ~$0.99/mo), you can use **Custom Email Domain** and create aliases like:
  - `support@freestylefit.net`
  - `privacy@freestylefit.net`
- This is usually the lowest-cost “proper mailbox” path.

#### Option C (cheap business mailbox): **Zoho Mail Lite** (send/receive)
- Typically ~$1/user/month.
- Works well for a single shared inbox (e.g., `support@freestylefit.net`) with proper SPF/DKIM.

### My recommendation
- If you want **the absolute cheapest** and you’re okay receiving-only: **GoDaddy forwarding**.
- If you want to **send and receive professionally** without spending much: **iCloud+ custom domain** (if you already have iCloud+), otherwise **Zoho Lite**.
